I've found that some people appreciate this kind of communication, and sometimes it's easier to explain a concept with association instead of words. Learning to unmask has been so hard because sometimes we don't realize how deeply that mask has worked its roots in out psyche.

I was able to adapt to this by making a sort of "game" out of putting those images to words, so that I can communicate appropriately. I love poetry for this reason; it allows me to translate my thoughts in their most direct translation, which is all creative imagery. (2)

I've realized that I mask by suppressing associative thinking patterns in conversation. Nearly every time I interact with people, I hear songs and see images. When I'm listening to someone, it's as if they're narrating or scoring a movie in my head (1)

@ADDeeCee @BiggMattWeaford The most "classic" representation of bipolar is a manic episode followed by a depressive episode, cycling between the two. To have a clinic diagnosis, you only need one depressive episode and one hypo/manic episode. How you cycle between the two is individual.

@ADDeeCee @BiggMattWeaford There are a few different "patterns" of bipolar, and with nearly everything, it's sort of a spectrum now. The difference in type I & II isn't severity, it's whether the person experiences severe mania, typically psychosis. The depressive episodes for type II can be long & severe.
